<component id="ID_minfo03">
	<text><![CDATA[One of the categorization methods used is a 2-by-2 matrix, with the rows being structured and unstructured attacks and the columns being internal and external threats. In this manner, attacks are categorized as either structured internal, structured external, unstructured internal, or unstructured external.<BR/><BR/>In 2001, the National Infrastructure Protection Center at the FBI released a document summarizing the Ten Most Critical Internet Security Vulnerabilities. Since that time, thousands of organizations relied on this list to prioritize their efforts so they can close the most dangerous holes first. According to representatives from the NIPC, the threat landscape is very dynamic, which in turn makes it necessary to adopt newer security measures. Over the last few years, the kinds of vulnerabilities that are being exploited are very different from the ones that were being exploited in the past.<BR/><BR/>In one alternative categorization schema for attacks, the types of attacks are classified as a function of the type of threat:<ul><li>Impersonation</li><li>Eavesdropping</li><li>Denial of Service</li><li>Packet replay</li><li>Man-in-the-middle</li><li>Packet modification</li></ul><BR/>There are several examples of these types of threats:<ul><li>ARP Attack</li><li>Brute Force Attack</li><li>Worms</li><li>Flooding</li><li>Sniffers</li><li>Spoofing</li><li>Redirected Attacks</li><li>Tunneling Attack</li><li>Covert Channels</li></ul><BR/>]]></text>
</component>


